ANNOUNCEMENT:

We are very pleased to inform you that our very own Pathfit Prof. Jan Hector Obando, MAT-PE, LPT, has been designated a NATIONAL COACH for volleyball by the Philippine National Volleyball Federation, effective July 1, 2023. Prof. Obando was able to obtain this certification by completing a series of written and practical examinations on volleyball from June 27 to July 1, 2023 at the Lourdes College Gymnasium in Cagayan de Oro City.

Furthermore, Prof. Obando‚Äôs excellent showing in the exams landed him in the top 10 list, making him eligible to join the International Certificate Course 2023 on July 24-28, 2023 at the Rizal Memorial Stadium, Manila.

This is yet another testimonial to the USJ-R School of Education‚Äôs unparalleled excellence when it comes to molding its faculty members to become the best versions of themselves and outcompete the rest of the field.

Congratulations on this milestone, Sir Jan! Your USJ-R SED family is so proud of you! Adelante!

The USJ-R School of Law officially launched the USJ-R School of Law Advocacy and Community Enrichment (SOLACE), the school's legal clinic on June 17, 2023 at the USJ-R Basak Campus.

Present in the launching were the representatives from the eighty (80) barangays of Cebu; Dean Jonathan P. Capanas, CPA, Dean of the USJ-R School of Law; Atty. Gonzalo D. Maligo-on, Jr., USJ-R Solace Legal Clinic Director; Atty. Virginia Palanca - Santiago, President of the Legal Alternatives for Women, Inc.;Atty. Pedro Leslie B. Salva, President of the USJ-R School of Law Alumni Association; Atty. Michael Francis L. Hubahib, President of the IBP Cebu Chapter; Atty. Christian Arenajo from IBP Cebu City Chapter, Hon. Leocadio T. Trovela, CESO III, Regional Director of DILG Region VII; Atty Ian Kenneth B. Lucero, MPSA, Provincial Director of DILG Sugbo; Hon. Marlon Jay G. Moneva, the Executive Judge of RTC Cebu City, Hon. Franklyn O. Ong, President of the Cebu City Liga ng mga Barangay; and Rev. Fr. Eduardo S. Celiz Jr. OAR, President of the University of San Jose - Recoletos to manifest their full support to the program.

Atty. Emiliano C. Tiongco, Jr, Executive Labor Arbiter of the National Labor Relations Commission and Atty. Mae Elaine T. Bathan, Assitant Dean of the USJ-R School of Law and Undersecretary of Tourism also expressed their message of support during the activity.

To all Josenian College Admission Test (JCAT) applicants:

1 Secure first an applicant number through filling out the admission form at https://edp.usjr.edu.ph/applicant/admission_form/. Make sure to submit the application for admission before taking the entrance examination for record purposes and to generate test results.

2 After securing an applicant number, fill-out the JCAT appointment form at https://forms.gle/7SSR79kY3Zq5XUCj6 and choose a schedule.

Here is the updated JCAT schedule starting June 5, 2023.
Weekdays (Monday to Friday)
Morning : 09:00 am - 10:30 am & 10:30 am -11:30 am
Afternoon : 01:30 pm - 02:30 pm & 02:30 pm - 3:30 pm

3 Visit USJ-R Main Campus and proceed to the Student Development and Placement Center (SDPC).

4 Present the requirements (applicant number, 2x2 colored picture with white background, certified true copy and photocopy of grades).

5 Fill-out the admission test form which will be provided at the SDPC after presenting your requirements.

6 Take the exam. Make sure to bring a pencil (Monggol #2) and black ballpen.

7 Interpretation of the test result by the counselor assigned shall be done during the releasing of the test result.

8 If the remark of the result is ‚ÄúPassed‚Äù or ‚ÄúProbationary‚Äù ‚Äì wait for the approval of the Department Chair in the SIS account. If the remark is ‚ÄúPlease see the Dean/Chair‚Äù , please approach the respective Chair/Dean for further interview and assessment.

9 One approved by the Chair/Dean, proceed to the Accounting Office and pay the enrollment fee.

10 Congratulations! You are now a bonafide student of the University.

11 Access the SIS portal to select your subjects for this semester.

12 The subjects that you selected will be approved by the Chair assigned for your degree program.

13 Once approved, you can send your study load (copy of all your subjects & schedule) to your email.

14 Attend your class starting August 7, 2023. Further orientation will be announced through the University‚Äôs digital platforms.

The 125th Anniversary of Philippine Independence and Nationhood is a multi-year commemoration of the 125th anniversary of the proclamation of Philippine independence and the allied historical events that brought about the founding of the Filipino nation from 1898 to 1901.

With the theme Kalayaan, Kinabukasan, Kasaysayan, it aims to serve as a milestone for the Filipino people to reflect on our journey as a free and independent people and how far we have gone from the dreams and aspirations of our forebears. It also highlights the role of our history in our journey as a people, to serve as a reminder of where we began from and of our goals as a country.

USJ-R SED Treats Japanese Visitors to Unforgettable Campus Visit

In an experience they will remember and cherish for the rest of their lives, students and teachers from Nishi Yamato High School were both literally and figuratively treated to a one-of-a-kind edu-cultural immersion last June 10, 2023, at the University of Jose-Recoletos Basak Campus Auditorium.

The program started with the opening remarks from Rev. Fr. Persiuz Decena, OAR, warmly welcoming the visitors from Nara Prefecture to the campus. Dr. Jestoni Babia, the former Dean of the USJ-R School of Education and Director of the Center of Education for Sustainable Development (ESD) gave a very robust speech on the importance of cross-cultural activities especially in light of common ground pertaining to sustainable initiatives and socio-environmental consciousness.

Emphasizing the strategic significance of the USJ-R School of Education as a hub for both academic excellence and sustainable education, Prof. Ma. Aira Chenessa B. Aguilar, Chair of the Department of Teacher Education, laid out key milestones and achievements of the college that ranged from multiple won competitions on innovative pandemic-era teaching practices to various Scopus-indexed publications with particular focus on best scientific and research-based sustainability efforts. It is worth noting that the School of Education has been designated a Center of Excellence in Teacher Education since 1996.

Prof. Justine Marie Munez, Adviser of the Josenian Educators (JOED) organization, gave a detailed presentation of JOED‚Äôs ongoing efforts to continue aligning its priorities with those of the United Nations Educational, Scientific, and Cultural Organization (UNESCO), particularly in the UN‚Äôs Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs). She enumerated several completed and future projects JOED has undertaken and will take part in to demonstrate the organization‚Äôs laserlike focus on training Josenian educators not only to become quality teachers in the classroom but individuals who can be counted upon as responsible global citizens in a constantly changing society.

After a series of presentations on the intricacies of the Philippine educational system and Filipino culture, the Japanese visitors were on the receiving end of the ‚Äúlearning by doing‚Äù instructional approach as the JOED officers and selected SED students, in various stations, showcased the unique and original Filipino cuisine, dances, and games, and invited the Japanese students to take part in each category. The primary point of this segment of the program was to introduce the visitors to the rich cultural legacy of the Filipinos and to steer them toward appreciating these unique cultural attributes while recognizing the value of USJ-R SED as an institution firmly committed to cross-cultural efforts to enhance the sharing of best practices and prioritizing the pursuit of common goals toward a sustainable future.

The success of the cultural immersion by our Japanese friends was yet another feather in the cap for the USJ-R School of Education and Josenian Educators organization in our continued drive toward the enhancement of the multi-pronged areas of quality instruction, strategic internationalization, and global citizenship. With this effort, expect more meaningful collaboration and productive partnerships to ensue between the School of Education and various entities from the governmental, civic, and academic communities from here and abroad to be forged and fostered. The continued exchange and sharing of innovative and forward-looking ideas and initiatives will only serve to help us in the School of Education deliver the kind of education and learning to mold our students in ultimately becoming not just excellent teachers in the classroom, but competent and reliable stewards of the world.

Happy Independence Day üáµüá≠

The 125th anniversary of Philippine Independence and Nationhood will be celebrated until 2026, with the theme ‚ÄúKalayaan. Kinabukasan. Kasaysayan. (Freedom. Future. History.).‚Äù

The flagship project of the commemoration, headed by the National Historical Commission of the Philippines, is the marking of around 100 sites, ranging from Kawit, Cavite where independence was declared on June 12, 1898, to Palanan, Isabela where President Emilio Aguinaldo was captured, an event which marked the end of the first Filipino government.

A week before the feast day of Our Lady of Mt. Carmel, nine dance groups participated in the offertory dance as part of the annual Bulak sa Carmel Festival.

One of which is the Adelante Dance Troupe of the University of San Jose-Recoletos.

The performances and the procession of andas decorated with fresh flowers were done along Magallanes Street this afternoon despite the rain.

text:
USJ-R SED Treats Japanese Visitors to Unforgettable Campus Visit

In an experience they will remember and cherish for the rest of their lives, students and teachers from Nishi Yamato High School were both literally and figuratively treated to a one-of-a-kind edu-cultural immersion last June 10, 2023, at the University of Jose-Recoletos Basak Campus Auditorium.

The program started with the opening remarks from Rev. Fr. Persiuz Decena, OAR, warmly welcoming the visitors from Nara Prefecture to the campus. Dr. Jestoni Babia, the former Dean of the USJ-R School of Education and Director of the Center of Education for Sustainable Development (ESD) gave a very robust speech on the importance of cross-cultural activities especially in light of common ground pertaining to sustainable initiatives and socio-environmental consciousness.

Emphasizing the strategic significance of the USJ-R School of Education as a hub for both academic excellence and sustainable education, Prof. Ma. Aira Chenessa B. Aguilar, Chair of the Department of Teacher Education, laid out key milestones and achievements of the college that ranged from multiple won competitions on innovative pandemic-era teaching practices to various Scopus-indexed publications with particular focus on best scientific and research-based sustainability efforts. It is worth noting that the School of Education has been designated a Center of Excellence in Teacher Education since 1996.

Prof. Justine Marie Munez, Adviser of the Josenian Educators (JOED) organization, gave a detailed presentation of JOED‚Äôs ongoing efforts to continue aligning its priorities with those of the United Nations Educational, Scientific, and Cultural Organization (UNESCO), particularly in the UN‚Äôs Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs). She enumerated several completed and future projects JOED has undertaken and will take part in to demonstrate the organization‚Äôs laserlike focus on training Josenian educators not only to become quality teachers in the classroom but individuals who can be counted upon as responsible global citizens in a constantly changing society.

After a series of presentations on the intricacies of the Philippine educational system and Filipino culture, the Japanese visitors were on the receiving end of the ‚Äúlearning by doing‚Äù instructional approach as the JOED officers and selected SED students, in various stations, showcased the unique and original Filipino cuisine, dances, and games, and invited the Japanese students to take part in each category. The primary point of this segment of the program was to introduce the visitors to the rich cultural legacy of the Filipinos and to steer them toward appreciating these unique cultural attributes while recognizing the value of USJ-R SED as an institution firmly committed to cross-cultural efforts to enhance the sharing of best practices and prioritizing the pursuit of common goals toward a sustainable future.

The success of the cultural immersion by our Japanese friends was yet another feather in the cap for the USJ-R School of Education and Josenian Educators organization in our continued drive toward the enhancement of the multi-pronged areas of quality instruction, strategic internationalization, and global citizenship. With this effort, expect more meaningful collaboration and productive partnerships to ensue between the School of Education and various entities from the governmental, civic, and academic communities from here and abroad to be forged and fostered. The continued exchange and sharing of innovative and forward-looking ideas and initiatives will only serve to help us in the School of Education deliver the kind of education and learning to mold our students in ultimately becoming not just excellent teachers in the classroom, but competent and reliable stewards of the world.

#SEDExcellence
#TakingYouForwardSince1947
#JosenianEducators

text:
Happy Independence Day üáµüá≠

The 125th anniversary of Philippine Independence and Nationhood will be celebrated until 2026, with the theme ‚ÄúKalayaan. Kinabukasan. Kasaysayan. (Freedom. Future. History.).‚Äù

The flagship project of the commemoration, headed by the National Historical Commission of the Philippines, is the marking of around 100 sites, ranging from Kawit, Cavite where independence was declared on June 12, 1898, to Palanan, Isabela where President Emilio Aguinaldo was captured, an event which marked the end of the first Filipino government.
ocr:
In celebration of the 125th Anniversary of Philippine Independence and Nationhood, the theme is "Kalayaan. Kasaysayan, Kinabukasan" which translates to "Freedom. History, Future" in English.

This theme highlights the importance of preserving and understanding the country's history as it serves as a foundation for the future. It emphasizes the significance of freedom and independence that the Philippines achieved and continues to uphold.

Through various activities and events, the 125th Anniversary aims to promote patriotism, unity, and love for the country. It encourages Filipinos to reflect on the past, appreciate the present, and work together towards a prosperous future.

Join us as we celebrate this momentous occasion and pay tribute to the heroes who fought for Philippine independence. Let us honor their sacrifices by embracing our responsibilities as citizens and by contributing to the development and progress of our nation.

Together, let's commemorate the 125th Anniversary of Philippine Independence and Nationhood with great pride, gratitude, and hope for a brighter future.

To all Josenian College Admission Test (JCAT) applicants:

1 Secure first an applicant number through filling out the admission form at https://edp.usjr.edu.ph/applicant/admission_form/. Make sure to submit the application for admission before taking the entrance examination for record purposes and to generate test results.

Weekdays (Monday to Friday)

text:
USJ-R SED Treats Japanese Visitors to Unforgettable Campus Visit

In an experience they will remember and cherish for the rest of their lives, students and teachers from Nishi Yamato High School were both literally and figuratively treated to a one-of-a-kind edu-cultural immersion last June 10, 2023, at the University of Jose-Recoletos Basak Campus Auditorium.

The program started with the opening remarks from Rev. Fr. Persiuz Decena, OAR, warmly welcoming the visitors from Nara Prefecture to the campus. Dr. Jestoni Babia, the former Dean of the USJ-R School of Education and Director of the Center of Education for Sustainable Development (ESD) gave a very robust speech on the importance of cross-cultural activities especially in light of common ground pertaining to sustainable initiatives and socio-environmental consciousness.

Emphasizing the strategic significance of the USJ-R School of Education as a hub for both academic excellence and sustainable education, Prof. Ma. Aira Chenessa B. Aguilar, Chair of the Department of Teacher Education, laid out key milestones and achievements of the college that ranged from multiple won competitions on innovative pandemic-era teaching practices to various Scopus-indexed publications with particular focus on best scientific and research-based sustainability efforts. It is worth noting that the School of Education has been designated a Center of Excellence in Teacher Education since 1996.

Prof. Justine Marie Munez, Adviser of the Josenian Educators (JOED) organization, gave a detailed presentation of JOED‚Äôs ongoing efforts to continue aligning its priorities with those of the United Nations Educational, Scientific, and Cultural Organization (UNESCO), particularly in the UN‚Äôs Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs). She enumerated several completed and future projects JOED has undertaken and will take part in to demonstrate the organization‚Äôs laserlike focus on training Josenian educators not only to become quality teachers in the classroom but individuals who can be counted upon as responsible global citizens in a constantly changing society.

After a series of presentations on the intricacies of the Philippine educational system and Filipino culture, the Japanese visitors were on the receiving end of the ‚Äúlearning by doing‚Äù instructional approach as the JOED officers and selected SED students, in various stations, showcased the unique and original Filipino cuisine, dances, and games, and invited the Japanese students to take part in each category. The primary point of this segment of the program was to introduce the visitors to the rich cultural legacy of the Filipinos and to steer them toward appreciating these unique cultural attributes while recognizing the value of USJ-R SED as an institution firmly committed to cross-cultural efforts to enhance the sharing of best practices and prioritizing the pursuit of common goals toward a sustainable future.

The success of the cultural immersion by our Japanese friends was yet another feather in the cap for the USJ-R School of Education and Josenian Educators organization in our continued drive toward the enhancement of the multi-pronged areas of quality instruction, strategic internationalization, and global citizenship. With this effort, expect more meaningful collaboration and productive partnerships to ensue between the School of Education and various entities from the governmental, civic, and academic communities from here and abroad to be forged and fostered. The continued exchange and sharing of innovative and forward-looking ideas and initiatives will only serve to help us in the School of Education deliver the kind of education and learning to mold our students in ultimately becoming not just excellent teachers in the classroom, but competent and reliable stewards of the world.

#SEDExcellence
#TakingYouForwardSince1947
#JosenianEducators

Happy Independence Day üáµüá≠

The 125th anniversary of Philippine Independence and Nationhood will be celebrated until 2026, with the theme ‚ÄúKalayaan. Kinabukasan. Kasaysayan. (Freedom. Future. History.).‚Äù

The flagship project of the commemoration, headed by the National Historical Commission of the Philippines, is the marking of around 100 sites, ranging from Kawit, Cavite where independence was declared on June 12, 1898, to Palanan, Isabela where President Emilio Aguinaldo was captured, an event which marked the end of the first Filipino government.
ocr:
Lapepunan lalapipuhin Dua Lalejiniputahingguin Kas Laken Satatattuwang Sya, Rasaunuin, Kaga Tingguin Kapubuwan lain Mbu.

Philippine Independence Day is an annual national holiday in the Philippines commemorating the country's declaration of independence from Spain on June 12, 1898. This year, 2023, marks the 125th anniversary of Philippine independence and nationhood.

The theme for this significant milestone is "Kalayaan. Kasaysayan, Kinabukasan." This theme highlights the importance of our freedom as a nation and recognizes the historical struggles and sacrifices that led to our independence. It also emphasizes the significance of our past in shaping our future, as we strive to build a better tomorrow for all Filipinos.

As we celebrate this momentous occasion, let us remember the brave heroes who fought for our freedom and honor their contributions to our nation. May this anniversary inspire us to continue working towards a more prosperous and united Philippines.

To commemorate the 125th anniversary of Philippine independence, various events and activities will be held throughout the country. These may include parades, flag-raising ceremonies, cultural performances, historical exhibits, and interactive educational programs. Citizens are encouraged to participate in these celebrations and deepen their understanding of our history and heritage.

Let us come together as one nation, united in our love for our country, as we celebrate 125 years of Philippine independence and look forward to a brighter future. Kalayaan sa ating lahat!

ocr:
Financial management is a crucial aspect of personal and corporate success. It involves making wise decisions about money, such as budgeting, investing, and planning for the future. For students at Paraiba ABM Senior High School, learning about financial management is essential as it will equip them with the skills and knowledge to lead financially stable lives.

To excel in financial management, students should start by understanding the fundamentals of personal finance. This includes creating a budget to track income and expenses, setting financial goals, and saving for emergencies or future expenses like education or a home.

Investment planning is another key component of financial management. Students can be introduced to basic investment principles like diversification, risk assessment, and the power of compound interest. Understanding these concepts will enable them to make informed decisions about investing their money wisely and building wealth over time.

Lastly, students should also learn about long-term financial planning. This involves understanding concepts like retirement planning, insurance coverage, and estate planning. By having a clear understanding of these topics, students will be better prepared to manage their finances throughout their lives.

To support the financial management education of Paraiba ABM Senior High students, it would be beneficial to provide workshops, resources, and activities that promote financial literacy. Inviting guest speakers from the finance industry or organizing field trips to financial institutions can provide students with real-world examples and experiences. Additionally, incorporating practical exercises like creating personal budgets or simulated investment portfolios can help students apply their knowledge in a hands-on manner.

In conclusion, financial management is a crucial skill for all individuals, including students. By equipping Paraiba ABM Senior High students with a strong understanding of financial management principles, they will be well-prepared to navigate their personal finances successfully and make informed decisions that can positively impact their futures.

#JosenianPride | A Josenian lawyer becomes the first woman elected as chair of The Hague Conference on Private International Law (HCCH) in the Netherlands!

Meet Atty. Marisar Ivy Cabatingan, third secretary and vice consul of the Philippine Embassy in The Hague.

She was elected as chair of the Standing Committee of the Council of Diplomatic Representatives of HCCH on May 23, making her the first woman to assume the post. The HCCH is an intergovernmental organization that administers international conventions related to private international law.

Cabatingan is an alumna of University of San Jose-Recoletos School of Law

Philippine Embassy in The Netherlands
May 29 at 1:24 PM ¬∑

PH EMBASSY‚ÄôS OFFICIAL MAKES HISTORY AS FIRST WOMAN ELECTED AS CHAIR OF HCCH STANDING COMMITTEE

Atty. Marisar Ivy Cabatingan, Third Secretary and Vice Consul of the Philippine Embassy in The Hague, was elected Chair of the Standing Committee of the Council of Diplomatic Representatives (CDR) of the Hague Conference on Private International Law (HCCH) during the 69th meeting of the CDR on May 23 at the Peace Palace in The Hague.

‚ÄúWe thank the members of the Council for the trust and confidence they have reposed on Ms. Cabatingan. The Philippines is pleased to further contribute to the work of the HCCH through her,‚Äù Ambassador J. Eduardo Malaya said. ‚ÄúThis development demonstrates the country's proactive engagement with international legal organizations and commitment to the vital role of the HCCH.‚Äù

Atty. Cabatingan is the first woman to assume the Chairmanship of the CDR Standing Committee. She previously served as CDR‚Äôs Vice Chairperson since May 2022.

She is an alumna of the University of San Jose Recoletos College of Law in Cebu.

Embassy of Poland‚Äôs First Secretary Paulina Dudzik was also elected as Vice Chair of the Standing Committee of the CDR, which demonstrated the commendable efforts of the HCCH in ensuring geographical representation and gender balance within the leadership roles of the organization.

The HCCH is an intergovernmental organization that administers international conventions related to private international law. The Philippines has acceded to several conventions under the HCCH, including the Inter-Country Adoption Convention, the Convention on the Civil Aspects of Child Abduction, the Apostille Convention, the Service Convention, and the Child Support Convention. With a membership of 91, consisting of 90 States and one regional economic integration organization (the European Union), the HCCH facilitates cooperation among nations in the aspects of private international law.

The HCCH-CDR comprises Ambassadors of the HCCH Member States or their designated representatives and serves as the supreme authority in matters of finance and budget within the HCCH. It exercises oversight on financial administration and is chaired by the Netherlands Minister of Foreign Affairs. The Standing Committee, on the other hand, which is led by a member elected from the CDR, supports its work and deliberates on financial and budgetary concerns raised by any Member State or the HCCH Secretary General. // END
ocr: That is fantastic news! It is always inspiring to see women breaking barriers and making history in various fields, including diplomacy. It demonstrates the progress towards gender equality and the recognition of women's capabilities in leadership roles. Congratulations to the official for her achievement as the first woman elected as chair of the Hoch Standing Committee.

RAISE YOUR FLAG! üáµüá≠

On May 28, 1898, the Philippine Flag was first unfurled after the Philippine Revolutionary Army won against the Spanish Forces in Imus, Cavite.

As the country marks today the National Flag Day, get to know the meanings behind the Filipino flag.
ocr:
The Philippine flag is the national flag of the Philippines and is an important symbol of national identity. It is composed of a horizontal rectangular design with a ratio of 1:2. The flag consists of two main colors: blue on top and red at the bottom, symbolizing peace, truth, and justice (blue) and patriotism and valor (red).

In the middle of the blue stripe, there is an equilateral triangle with a white border containing three yellow five-pointed stars. Each star represents the three main geographical regions of the Philippines: Luzon, Visayas, and Mindanao.

Inside the triangle, there is a yellow sun with eight rays representing the eight provinces that first revolted against Spanish colonial rule. The sun's face symbolizes liberty, while the rays represent the first eight provinces that fought for independence.

The Philippine flag has a deep historical significance and has undergone several changes in design throughout the years. It was first conceptualized by General Emilio Aguinaldo, the first President of the Philippines, and was officially adopted on June 12, 1898.

Every year, May 28 is celebrated as National Flag Day in the Philippines to promote patriotism and raise awareness about the importance of the national flag in Filipino society. It serves as a reminder of the country's struggles for freedom and sovereignty.

The Philippine flag is proudly displayed in various locations, such as government buildings, schools, and during national holidays and events. It symbolizes the Filipino people's unity, courage, and love for their country.

text:
USJ-R SED Treats Japanese Visitors to Unforgettable Campus Visit

In an experience they will remember and cherish for the rest of their lives, students and teachers from Nishi Yamato High School were both literally and figuratively treated to a one-of-a-kind edu-cultural immersion last June 10, 2023, at the University of Jose-Recoletos Basak Campus Auditorium.

The program started with the opening remarks from Rev. Fr. Persiuz Decena, OAR, warmly welcoming the visitors from Nara Prefecture to the campus. Dr. Jestoni Babia, the former Dean of the USJ-R School of Education and Director of the Center of Education for Sustainable Development (ESD) gave a very robust speech on the importance of cross-cultural activities especially in light of common ground pertaining to sustainable initiatives and socio-environmental consciousness.

Emphasizing the strategic significance of the USJ-R School of Education as a hub for both academic excellence and sustainable education, Prof. Ma. Aira Chenessa B. Aguilar, Chair of the Department of Teacher Education, laid out key milestones and achievements of the college that ranged from multiple won competitions on innovative pandemic-era teaching practices to various Scopus-indexed publications with particular focus on best scientific and research-based sustainability efforts. It is worth noting that the School of Education has been designated a Center of Excellence in Teacher Education since 1996.

Prof. Justine Marie Munez, Adviser of the Josenian Educators (JOED) organization, gave a detailed presentation of JOED‚Äôs ongoing efforts to continue aligning its priorities with those of the United Nations Educational, Scientific, and Cultural Organization (UNESCO), particularly in the UN‚Äôs Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs). She enumerated several completed and future projects JOED has undertaken and will take part in to demonstrate the organization‚Äôs laserlike focus on training Josenian educators not only to become quality teachers in the classroom but individuals who can be counted upon as responsible global citizens in a constantly changing society.

After a series of presentations on the intricacies of the Philippine educational system and Filipino culture, the Japanese visitors were on the receiving end of the ‚Äúlearning by doing‚Äù instructional approach as the JOED officers and selected SED students, in various stations, showcased the unique and original Filipino cuisine, dances, and games, and invited the Japanese students to take part in each category. The primary point of this segment of the program was to introduce the visitors to the rich cultural legacy of the Filipinos and to steer them toward appreciating these unique cultural attributes while recognizing the value of USJ-R SED as an institution firmly committed to cross-cultural efforts to enhance the sharing of best practices and prioritizing the pursuit of common goals toward a sustainable future.

The success of the cultural immersion by our Japanese friends was yet another feather in the cap for the USJ-R School of Education and Josenian Educators organization in our continued drive toward the enhancement of the multi-pronged areas of quality instruction, strategic internationalization, and global citizenship. With this effort, expect more meaningful collaboration and productive partnerships to ensue between the School of Education and various entities from the governmental, civic, and academic communities from here and abroad to be forged and fostered. The continued exchange and sharing of innovative and forward-looking ideas and initiatives will only serve to help us in the School of Education deliver the kind of education and learning to mold our students in ultimately becoming not just excellent teachers in the classroom, but competent and reliable stewards of the world.

#SEDExcellence
#TakingYouForwardSince1947
#JosenianEducators

Happy Independence Day üáµüá≠

The 125th anniversary of Philippine Independence and Nationhood will be celebrated until 2026, with the theme ‚ÄúKalayaan. Kinabukasan. Kasaysayan. (Freedom. Future. History.).‚Äù

The flagship project of the commemoration, headed by the National Historical Commission of the Philippines, is the marking of around 100 sites, ranging from Kawit, Cavite where independence was declared on June 12, 1898, to Palanan, Isabela where President Emilio Aguinaldo was captured, an event which marked the end of the first Filipino government.
ocr:
125th Anniversary of Philippine Independence and Nationhood

Kalayaan. Kasaysayan, Kinabukasan.

In celebration of the 125th anniversary of Philippine independence and the nation's rich history, we invite you to join us in honoring our past, embracing our present, and building a bright future together.

This momentous occasion is a tribute to the bravery and resilience of our forefathers who fought for our freedom from colonial rule. It is a reminder of the sacrifices made and the battles won to forge our identity as an independent nation.

Throughout the years, we have faced numerous challenges and triumphs. From the struggles of the past to the accomplishments of the present, we have shown the world what it truly means to be a Filipino.

As we mark this milestone, let us remember and honor the heroes who have paved the way for our freedom. Let us reflect on our shared history and the lessons it teaches us. And let us look forward to a future filled with unity, progress, and prosperity.

Join us in celebrating the 125th anniversary of Philippine independence and nationhood. Together, let us create a stronger, more inclusive, and brighter future for all Filipinos.

#Kalayaan125
#PhilippineIndependence
#Nationhood

ocr:
When it comes to financial management, it's important to have a clear understanding of your goals and develop a plan to achieve them. One effective financial management tool is called the PARAIBA method, which can be implemented by senior high students at ABM track in Min COM IS-R.

PARAIBA stands for:

1. Prioritize: Start by identifying your financial goals and priorities. Whether it's saving for college, buying a car, or starting a business, determine what matters most to you.

2. Assess: Take a comprehensive look at your current financial situation. Evaluate your income, expenses, assets, and liabilities. This will help you gain a clearer picture of where you stand financially.

3. Research: Invest time in researching financial strategies and products that align with your goals. Explore different investment options, savings accounts, and credit cards. The more informed you are, the better decisions you can make.

4. Allocate: Create a budget to allocate your income towards various expenses and savings goals. This will help you prioritize your spending and ensure you're on track to meet your financial objectives.

5. Implement: Put your plan into action. Start saving, investing, and tracking your expenses. Stay disciplined and consistent in following your financial management strategy.

6. Budget: Continuously reassess and adjust your budget as needed. Regularly monitor your expenses and income to ensure you are staying within your financial goals.

7. Analyze: Regularly review your progress and evaluate if your financial plan is working for you. Make any necessary adjustments based on your analysis.

By applying the PARAIBA method, senior high students at ABM track in Min COM IS-R can gain a solid foundation in financial management and set themselves up for a financially responsible future.

ocr:
Congratulations on your goal to pass the May 2025 licensure exams for Certified Public Accountants! Obtaining this certification is a significant achievement that can open up a variety of career opportunities in the field of accounting. To increase your chances of success, it's essential to have a well-structured study plan and utilize effective study techniques. Here are a few general tips to help you prepare:

1. Create a study schedule: Develop a study plan that includes specific deadlines and targets for each subject. Allocate dedicated time for reviewing course materials, practicing sample questions, and taking mock exams.

2. Understand the exam format: Familiarize yourself with the exam structure, content, and time allocation for each section. This knowledge will help you tailor your preparation and allocate time according to the weightage of each topic.

3. Utilize study materials: Gather relevant study materials, including textbooks, online resources, practice exams, and study guides. Ensure that the resources you choose align with the exam syllabus and cover all essential topics.

4. Practice with mock exams: Taking mock exams will help you gauge your readiness, identify weak areas, and improve your time management skills. Try to simulate exam-like conditions as much as possible to get a realistic experience.

5. Join study groups or online forums: Engage with fellow candidates who are also preparing for the same exams. Discussing concepts, asking questions, and sharing study strategies can enhance your understanding and provide different perspectives on various topics.

6. Focus on weak areas: Identify the areas where you feel less confident and allocate extra time for improvement. Revise concepts, practice questions, and seek clarification from tutors, if needed.

7. Stay organized: Keep your study materials and notes well-organized to avoid confusion and save time during revision. Use color-coded labels or digital tools to manage your study resources efficiently.

8. Take care of yourself: Don't neglect your physical and mental health during this time. Ensure you get enough rest, eat a balanced diet, exercise regularly, and take breaks to relax and rejuvenate.

Remember to stay committed, motivated, and disciplined throughout your preparation journey. With consistent effort, a clear study plan, and effective study techniques, you have a great chance of passing the May 2025 CPA licensure exams. Good luck!

#JosenianPride | A Josenian lawyer becomes the first woman elected as chair of The Hague Conference on Private International Law (HCCH) in the Netherlands!

Meet Atty. Marisar Ivy Cabatingan, third secretary and vice consul of the Philippine Embassy in The Hague.

She was elected as chair of the Standing Committee of the Council of Diplomatic Representatives of HCCH on May 23, making her the first woman to assume the post. The HCCH is an intergovernmental organization that administers international conventions related to private international law.

Cabatingan is an alumna of University of San Jose-Recoletos School of Law

Philippine Embassy in The Netherlands
May 29 at 1:24 PM ¬∑

PH EMBASSY‚ÄôS OFFICIAL MAKES HISTORY AS FIRST WOMAN ELECTED AS CHAIR OF HCCH STANDING COMMITTEE

Atty. Marisar Ivy Cabatingan, Third Secretary and Vice Consul of the Philippine Embassy in The Hague, was elected Chair of the Standing Committee of the Council of Diplomatic Representatives (CDR) of the Hague Conference on Private International Law (HCCH) during the 69th meeting of the CDR on May 23 at the Peace Palace in The Hague.

‚ÄúWe thank the members of the Council for the trust and confidence they have reposed on Ms. Cabatingan. The Philippines is pleased to further contribute to the work of the HCCH through her,‚Äù Ambassador J. Eduardo Malaya said. ‚ÄúThis development demonstrates the country's proactive engagement with international legal organizations and commitment to the vital role of the HCCH.‚Äù

Atty. Cabatingan is the first woman to assume the Chairmanship of the CDR Standing Committee. She previously served as CDR‚Äôs Vice Chairperson since May 2022.

She is an alumna of the University of San Jose Recoletos College of Law in Cebu.

Embassy of Poland‚Äôs First Secretary Paulina Dudzik was also elected as Vice Chair of the Standing Committee of the CDR, which demonstrated the commendable efforts of the HCCH in ensuring geographical representation and gender balance within the leadership roles of the organization.

The HCCH is an intergovernmental organization that administers international conventions related to private international law. The Philippines has acceded to several conventions under the HCCH, including the Inter-Country Adoption Convention, the Convention on the Civil Aspects of Child Abduction, the Apostille Convention, the Service Convention, and the Child Support Convention. With a membership of 91, consisting of 90 States and one regional economic integration organization (the European Union), the HCCH facilitates cooperation among nations in the aspects of private international law.

The HCCH-CDR comprises Ambassadors of the HCCH Member States or their designated representatives and serves as the supreme authority in matters of finance and budget within the HCCH. It exercises oversight on financial administration and is chaired by the Netherlands Minister of Foreign Affairs. The Standing Committee, on the other hand, which is led by a member elected from the CDR, supports its work and deliberates on financial and budgetary concerns raised by any Member State or the HCCH Secretary General. // END

RAISE YOUR FLAG! üáµüá≠

On May 28, 1898, the Philippine Flag was first unfurled after the Philippine Revolutionary Army won against the Spanish Forces in Imus, Cavite.

As the country marks today the National Flag Day, get to know the meanings behind the Filipino flag.
ocr:
The Philippine Flag is the national flag of the Republic of the Philippines. It symbolizes the country's independence, sovereignty, and patriotism. The flag consists of a rectangular design with a blue horizontal stripe at the top and a red horizontal stripe at the bottom. In between the blue and red stripes is a white equilateral triangle with an eight-rayed golden yellow sun at the center. Inside the triangle are three stars, representing the three main geographical regions of the Philippines: Luzon, Visayas, and Mindanao. The Philippine flag is widely respected and is displayed prominently on public buildings, schools, and homes across the country. 

National Flag Day is celebrated in the Philippines on May 28th of every year. It commemorates the day in 1898 when the Philippine flag was first unfurled and adopted as the national flag of the country. This day is an opportunity for Filipinos to display their national pride and honor the significance of the flag as a symbol of unity and freedom. Various ceremonies, parades, and events are held nationwide to pay tribute to the Philippine flag and its importance in the nation's history.

Furthermore, Prof. Obando‚Äôs excellent showing in the exams landed him in the top 10 list, making him eligible to join the International Certificate Course 2023 on July 24-28, 2023 at the Rizal Memorial Stadium, Manila.

This is yet another testimonial to the USJ-R School of Education‚Äôs unparalleled excellence when it comes to molding its faculty members to become the best versions of themselves and outcompete the rest of the field.

Congratulations on this milestone, Sir Jan! Your USJ-R SED family is so proud of you! Adelante!

Parish Catechists from the Far North District Catechetical Ministry of the Archdiocese of Cebu were immersed in a two-day seminar and workshop on how to provide basic faith formation orientation.

Participants number to 180 catechists and 2 priests, from a total of 16 parishes.

The San Isidro Labrador Parish in Daanbantayan town took the initiative to host this seminar-workshop, recognizing the importance of empowering catechists in their mission to provide quality faith formation within their communities.
